T1  - PRODUCTIVITY AND THE LABOR MARKET: COMOVEMENT OVER THE BUSINESS CYCLE*
AU  - Hagedorn, Marcus
AU  - Manovskii, Iourii
Y1  - 2011/08/01
PY  - 2011
DA  - 2011/08/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2011.00641.x
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
SP  - 603
EP  - 619
VL  - 52
IS  - 3
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2011.00641.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - The productivity-driven Mortensen?Pissarides model predicts that labor productivity is strongly correlated with labor market variables whereas these correlations were argued to be much weaker in the data, especially since the 1980s. We first document that the size of these discrepancies between the data and the model becomes substantially smaller if employment data from the Current Population Survey is used in measuring productivity instead of the commonly used employment data from the Current Employment Statistics. Second, we show that incorporating time to build and a stochastic value of home production helps reconcile the quantitative performance of the model with the data.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - ON THE IMPACT OF FUNDAMENTALS, LIQUIDITY, AND COORDINATION ON MARKET STABILITY*
AU  - Daníelsson, Jón
AU  - Peñaranda, Francisco
Y1  - 2011/08/01
PY  - 2011
DA  - 2011/08/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2011.00642.x
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
SP  - 621
EP  - 638
VL  - 52
IS  - 3
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2011.00642.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - We develop a coordination game to model interactions between fundamentals and liquidity during unstable periods in financial markets. We then propose a flexible econometric framework for estimation of the model and analysis of its quantitative implications. The specific empirical application is carry trades in the yen?dollar market, including the turmoil of 1998. We find a generally very deep market, with low information disparities among agents. We observe occasional episodes of market fragility or turmoil with?up by the escalator, down by the elevator?patterns in prices. The key role of strategic behavior in the econometric model is also confirmed.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - JOB SEARCH WITH BIDDER MEMORIES*
AU  - Carrillo-Tudela, Carlos
AU  - Menzio, Guido
AU  - Smith, Eric
Y1  - 2011/08/01
PY  - 2011
DA  - 2011/08/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2011.00643.x
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
SP  - 639
EP  - 655
VL  - 52
IS  - 3
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2011.00643.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - This article revisits the no-recall assumption in job search models with take-it-or-leave-it offers. Workers who can recall previously encountered potential employers in order to engage them in Bertrand bidding have a distinct advantage over workers without such attachments. Firms account for this difference when hiring a worker. When a worker first meets a firm, the firm offers the worker a sufficient share of the match rents to avoid a bidding war in the future. The pair share the gains to trade. In this case, the Diamond paradox no longer holds.
ER  - 

